This paper proposes a model for natural language sentence matching, which is a common task in natural language processing. The paper focuses on the matching-aggregation framework and proposes a bilateral multi-perspective matching (BiMPM) model. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also uses deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper evaluates the model on three tasks, including paraphrase identification (cs.CL), natural language inference (cs.CL), and answer sentence selection (cs.IR). Finally, the paper proposes a new model architecture, which could be of interest to researchers in neural networks (cs.NE).
